06233nam a22008415i 9780226309972DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20092001ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802263099727 a10.7208/97802263099722doi  a(DE-B1597)524048  a(OCoLC)1058439148  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL 4aHQ796.R554 2001 7aFAM0000002bisacsh04a305.235a305.235a339.4083500aRisky Behavior among Youths :bAn Economic Analysis /ced. by Jonathan Gruber. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2009] 4c©2001  a1 online resource (536 p.) :b86 line drawings, 87 tables  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aNational Bureau of Economic Research Conference Report00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- t1. Risky Behavior among Youths -- t2. Youth Smoking in the United States -- t3. Teens and Traffic Safety -- t4. The Sexual Activity and Birth-Control Use of American Teenagers -- t5. Explaining the Rise in Youth Suicide -- t6. Marijuana and Youth -- t7. The Determinants of Juvenile Crime -- t8. Environment and Persistence in Youthful Drinking Patterns -- t9. Dropout and Enrollment Trends in the Postwar Period -- t10. Youths at Nutrition Risk -- tContributors -- tAuthor Index -- tSubject Index0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aEvery day young people engage in risky behaviors that affect not only their immediate well-being but their long-term health and safety. These well-honed essays apply diverse economic analyses to a wide range of unsafe activities, including teen drinking and driving, smoking, drug use, unprotected sex, and criminal activity. Economic principles are further applied to mental health and performance issues such as teenage depression, suicide, nutritional disorders, and high school dropout rates. Together, the essays yield notable findings: price and regulatory incentives are critical determinants of high-risk behavior, suggesting that youths do apply some sort of cost/benefit calculation when making decisions; the macroeconomic environment in which those decisions are made matters greatly; and youths who pursue high-risk behaviors are significantly more likely to engage in similar behaviors as adults. This important volume provides both a key data source for public policy makers and a clear affirmation of the usefulness of economic analysis to our understanding of risky behavior.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aBusiness. 0aDecision making in adolescence. 0aRisk-taking (Psychology) in adolescence. 0aSocial sciences. 0aYouth. 7aFAMILY & RELATIONSHIPS / General.2bisacsh1 aBhattacharya, Jay, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCard, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChaloupka, Frank J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCook, Philip J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCurrie, Janet, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCutler, David M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDee, Thomas S., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEvans, William N., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFarrelly, Matthew C., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGlaeser, Edward L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGrossman, Michael, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGruber, Jonathan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGruber, Jonathan, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aJohnston